# State form conventions

## File structure per state (e.g. UT)

```
src/forms/Y20XX/stateForms/ST/
  index.ts       — default export: (f1040: F1040) => new MainForm(f1040)
  MainForm.ts    — extends StateForm, implements fields()
  Schedule.ts    — attachments (e.g. nonresident schedule)
  Parameters.ts  — tax rates, brackets, constants for the year
```

## Required properties

```typescript
export default class MainForm extends Form {
  formName = 'TC-40'        // must match PDF filename (without .pdf)
  state: State = 'UT'       // 2-letter abbreviation
  formOrder = 0             // ordering within same state
}
```

## fields() pattern

- Return `Field[]` with length matching the PDF field count exactly
- Use formgen output (`npm run formgen <pdf>`) to determine field indices
- Strings go to text fields, booleans to checkboxes, numbers are auto-rounded
- Use `undefined` for empty fields

## Nonresident detection

```typescript
isNonresident = (): boolean =>
  !this.info.stateResidencies.some((r) => r.state === 'ST')
```

## Income-state derivation

States are derived from `f1040.info.realEstate[].address.state`. Registration is in `Y20XX/stateForms/index.ts`. Only states with an entry in `stateForms` get forms generated.

## Common pitfalls

- PDF fields with `maxLength` will throw if the string is too long
- `displayRound()` returns `undefined` when the rounded value is 0
- ESLint with `CI=true` treats warnings as errors; avoid unnecessary conditionals
